com.stormpath.sdk.factor.google

Class GoogleAuthenticatorFactors

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.stormpath.sdk.factor.google.GoogleAuthenticatorFactors

  • public final class GoogleAuthenticatorFactors
extends Object
    Static utility/helper methods for working with GoogleAuthenticatorFactor resources. Most methods are factory methods used for forming GoogleAuthenticatorFactor-specific fluent DSL queries. For example: 
     Factors.GOOGLE_AUTHENTICATOR.where(Factors.GOOGLE_AUTHENTICATOR.status().eq(FactorStatus.ENABLED))
     .orderByStatus().descending()
     .withAccounts(10, 10)
     .offsetBy(50)
     .limitTo(25));
    or, if using static imports: 
     import static com.stormpath.sdk.factor.Factors.GOOGLE_AUTHENTICATOR.*;

 ...

 where(status().eq(FactorStatus.ENABLED))
     .orderByStatus().descending()
     .withAccounts(10, 10)
     .offsetBy(50)
     .limitTo(25));
    Since:
    1.1.0

      • criteria

        public static GoogleAuthenticatorFactorCriteria criteria()
        Returns a new GoogleAuthenticatorFactorCriteria instance to use to formulate a Factor query.

        Note that it is usually more common to use the where method instead of this one as the where method usually lends to better readability. For example: 

         Factors.criteria().add(Factors.GOOGLE_AUTHENTICATOR.status().eq(FactorStatus.ENABLED))...
        versus: 
         Factors.GOOGLE_AUTHENTICATOR.where(Factors.GOOGLE_AUTHENTICATOR.status().eq(FactorStatus.ENABLED))...
        or when using static imports: 
         where(status().eq(FactorStatus.ENABLED))
        While all three statements are equivalent, the second and third examples are shorter and probably more readable.
        Returns:
        a new GoogleAuthenticatorFactorCriteria instance to use to formulate a Factor query.

      • status

        public static EqualsExpressionFactory status()
        Creates a new EqualsExpressionFactory instance reflecting the GoogleAuthenticatorFactor status property, to be used to construct a status Criterion when building an GoogleAuthenticatorFactorCriteria query. For example: 
         Factors.GOOGLE_AUTHENTICATOR.where(Factors.GOOGLE_AUTHENTICATOR.status().eq(FactorStatus.ENABLED));
        The above example invokes the returned factory's eq() method. This produces a status-specific Criterion which is added to the criteria query (via the where method). For example, the following code is equivalent: 
         FactorCriteria criteria = Factors.criteria();
 StringExpressionFactory statusExpressionFactory = Factors.GOOGLE_AUTHENTICATOR.status();
 Criterion statusEqualsEnabled = statusExpressionFactory.eq(FactorStatus.ENABLED);
 criteria.add(statusEqualsEnabled);
        The first code example is clearly more succinct and readable.
        Returns:
        a new status-specific StringExpressionFactory instance, to be used to construct a criterion when building an FactorCriteria query.

      • verificationStatus

        public static EqualsExpressionFactory verificationStatus()
        Creates a new EqualsExpressionFactory instance reflecting the Factor status property, to be used to construct a status Criterion when building an FactorCriteria query. For example: 
         Factors.GOOGLE_AUTHENTICATOR.where(Factors.GOOGLE_AUTHENTICATOR.verificationStatus().eq(FactorVerificationStatus.VERIFIED));
        The above example invokes the returned factory's eq() method. This produces a status-specific Criterion which is added to the criteria query (via the where method). For example, the following code is equivalent: 
         FactorCriteria criteria = Factors.criteria();
 StringExpressionFactory statusExpressionFactory = Factors.status();
 Criterion statusEqualsVerified = statusExpressionFactory.eq(FactorStatus.ENABLED);
 criteria.add(statusEqualsEnabled);
        The first code example is clearly more succinct and readable.
        Returns:
        a new status-specific StringExpressionFactory instance, to be used to construct a criterion when building an FactorCriteria query.

      • createdAt

        public static DateExpressionFactory createdAt()
        Creates a new DateExpressionFactory instance reflecting the GoogleAuthenticatorFactor createdAt property, to be used to construct a createdAt Criterion when building an FactorCriteria query. For example: 
         Factors.where(Factors.SMS.createdAt().matches("[,2014-04-05T12:00:00]");
        The above example invokes the returned factory's matches("[,2014-04-05T12:00:00]")) method. This produces a name-specific Criterion which is added to the criteria query (via the where method). 
         For example, the following code is equivalent:
 
         FactorCriteria criteria = Factors.SMS.criteria();
 DateExpressionFactory createdAt = Factors.SMS.createdAt();
 Criterion createdAtMatches = createdAt.matches("[,2014-04-05T12:00:00]");
 criteria.add(createdAtMatches);
        Returns:
        a new createdAt-specific DateExpressionFactory instance, to be used to construct a criterion when building an FactorCriteria query.
        Since:
        1.0.RC4.6

      • modifiedAt

        public static DateExpressionFactory modifiedAt()
        Creates a new DateExpressionFactory instance reflecting the Group modifiedAt property, to be used to construct a modifiedAt Criterion when building an FactorCriteria query. For example: 
         Factors.where(Factors.SMS.modifiedAt().matches("[,2014-04-05T12:00:00]");
        The above example invokes the returned factory's matches("[,2014-04-05T12:00:00]")) method. This produces a name-specific Criterion which is added to the criteria query (via the where method). 
         For example, the following code is equivalent:
 
         FactorCriteria criteria = Factors.SMS.criteria();
 DateExpressionFactory modifiedAt = Factors.SMS.getModifiedAt();
 Criterion modifiedAtMatches = modifiedAt.matches("[,2014-04-05T12:00:00]");
 criteria.add(modifiedAtMatches);
        Returns:
        a new modifiedAt-specific DateExpressionFactory instance, to be used to construct a criterion when building an FactorCriteria query.
        Since:
        1.0.RC4.6
